CONTEXT = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The wilderness of Sin (<em>midbar Sin</em>) — a place name unrelated to the Hebrew word for sin (<em>chet</em>), possibly related to the Sinai toponym. The date — the fifteenth day of the second month — is exactly one month after the Exodus (the first month, Exod 12:2). The journey so far: Ramesses → Succoth → Etham → Red Sea crossing → Marah → Elim → now the wilderness of Sin. The community is still weeks from Sinai. The chronological note grounds the narrative in specific itinerary tradition.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The first wilderness complaint: the whole community grumbles (<em>vayilonu</em>) against Moses and Aaron. The grumbling becomes one of the defining patterns of the wilderness period — repeated in Num 11, 14, 16-17, 20-21. The complaint structure is consistent: present hardship → idealization of Egypt → accusation against Moses → YHWH's provision. The Hebrew verb <em>lun</em> (grumble, murmur) appears throughout the wilderness narrative as the technical term for Israel's covenant ingratitude. Numbers 11:1 says YHWH's anger burned when he heard their complaints; here in ch 16 YHWH responds with provision rather than judgment.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;If only we had died by YHWH's hand in Egypt! There we sat by the pots of meat and ate bread to the full.&rdquo; Historical amnesia: the Israelites were enslaved laborers who built Pharaoh's cities; the idealized memory of abundant food in Egypt is the comfort of bondage reconceived as prosperity. The psychology of liberation is accurately described: freedom under hardship can appear worse than security under oppression. Paul's warning against returning to &ldquo;the weak and beggarly elements&rdquo; (Gal 4:9) and the Corinthians' nostalgia for the worldly life (1 Cor 10:6-10) reflect the same dynamic the manna narrative is designed to address.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;I am going to rain bread from heaven for you.&rdquo; The phrase <em>mamlir lachem lechem min hashamayim</em> (raining bread from heaven) is the background for John 6:31-35, where the crowd cites Ps 78:24 (&ldquo;he gave them bread from heaven to eat&rdquo;) and Jesus corrects: &ldquo;It was not Moses who gave you the bread from heaven; my Father gives you the true bread from heaven.&rdquo; The manna is simultaneously provision and test (<em>lenasoto</em>): will the people gather only what is needed daily? The daily-bread economy tests the daily-trust that Sabbath and covenant require.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The double portion on the sixth day — before the Sabbath commandment is formally given at Sinai (20:8-11). The Sabbath rhythm is embedded in YHWH's provision structure before it is codified as law: the seventh day's rest is made possible by the sixth day's double gift. This sequence — divine provision enabling the commanded rest — establishes that Sabbath is not a burden imposed on human productivity but a rest made possible by YHWH's generosity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses and Aaron's interpretive announcement: &ldquo;By evening you will know that it was YHWH who brought you out of Egypt.&rdquo; The quail and manna are not merely food but self-revealing acts of YHWH — each serves an epistemic function. The double knowing (&ldquo;you will know&rdquo; in v6 and v12) frames the provision as revelation, not just sustenance. The same formula — &ldquo;you will know that I am YHWH&rdquo; — governs the plague narrative (7:17; 8:10, 22) and appears in Ezekiel over 70 times as YHWH's statement of purpose.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;In the morning you will see the glory of YHWH (<em>kevod YHWH</em>), because he has heard your grumbling against him.&rdquo; The kavod YHWH — the visible, radiant manifestation of the divine presence — appears in the cloud (v10). Its appearing in response to grumbling shows that YHWH answers complaint with presence and provision rather than judgment. The same kavod will fill the tabernacle (40:34-35) and the temple (1 Kgs 8:11). John 1:14 applies the language to the Incarnation: &ldquo;the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us, and we saw his glory.&rdquo;</p>",
    "8": "<p>Moses clarifies that the grumbling is not against him and Aaron but against YHWH: &ldquo;your grumblings are not against us but against YHWH.&rdquo; The same point recurs throughout the wilderness narrative (Num 14:27; 16:11; 17:5). The complaint against the human leader is always ultimately a complaint against the divine sender — a principle with consistent NT application: &ldquo;Whoever rejects you rejects me&rdquo; (Luke 10:16); &ldquo;whoever blasphemes the Holy Spirit&rdquo; (Mark 3:29).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Aaron summons the community to &ldquo;come before YHWH, for he has heard your grumbling.&rdquo; The assembly before YHWH anticipates the later liturgical assembly at the tabernacle. Aaron's mediatorial role — summoning the people to YHWH's presence in response to their complaint — establishes the priestly function as intermediary between a complaining community and a responding God.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The appearance of the kavod in the cloud — while Aaron was still speaking, the glory appeared. The immediacy of the divine response (before the speech is finished) demonstrates YHWH's active presence in the assembly. The cloud (<em>anan</em>) is the primary form of the divine presence in the wilderness: the pillar of cloud by day (13:21-22) that guides and protects Israel. Here it becomes the medium through which YHWH speaks and acts.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Brief transitional verse: YHWH speaks to Moses. The pattern — YHWH hears, YHWH speaks, YHWH provides — is the consistent structure of wilderness provision narratives (Num 11:18-23; 20:7-8). YHWH does not ignore complaint but engages it directly with word and action.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;I have heard the grumbling of the Israelites.&rdquo; YHWH hears and responds with double provision: meat in the evening and bread in the morning. The self-identification formula ends the promise: &ldquo;you will know that I am YHWH your God.&rdquo; The provision is revelation; the feeding is self-disclosure. Ps 78:17-29 recounts this as an example of YHWH's mercy toward a rebellious Israel — he provided even while they sinned.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The quail (<em>slaw</em>) come at evening. Quail migration is well-documented in the Sinai Peninsula — exhausted quail land in large numbers during spring migration along the coasts and inland routes. The phenomenon is a genuine natural one whose providential timing YHWH employs. Numbers 11:31-34 recounts a later quail episode where Israel's excess desire becomes judgment; here the quail are pure provision with no negative consequence. The morning dew covering the camp is the preparatory phenomenon for the manna.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The manna's physical appearance: thin, flaky (<em>dak mechuspas</em>), fine as frost. Various naturalistic proposals have been offered — the most frequently cited is the honeydew secretion of the Tamarisk scale insect (<em>Trabutina mannipara</em>), which produces a white crystalline substance in the Sinai region. But none of the natural analogues account for the 40-year supply, the Sabbath doubling, the afternoon melting, or the inability to keep it overnight. The narrative presents something that partakes of natural appearance while exceeding natural explanation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;What is it?&rdquo; — <em>man hu</em>, which gives the substance its name. The Hebrew wordplay: <em>man</em> may be an Aramaic/Egyptian borrowing meaning &ldquo;what?&rdquo; The name is the question — Israel calls it &ldquo;what?&rdquo; and the question remains unanswered until Jesus in John 6 says &ldquo;I am the bread of life&rdquo; (John 6:35). The manna is the OT's most sustained open question about the nature of divine bread; the NT closes it.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The omer (<em>omer</em>) measure — approximately 2 liters — one omer per person per day. The instruction introduces measured sufficiency: enough, but not excess. The gathering-by-head instruction ensures that provision is personal, not just communal: each individual's need is attended to by YHWH's economy. The contrast with Pharaoh's unlimited demand (ch 5) is implicit: YHWH's economy is sufficient and personal; Pharaoh's was insatiable and impersonal.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Israelites gather as instructed — some more, some less, according to their ability and the quantity available to them. The diversity of gathering effort is acknowledged without moral comment. What matters is not the amount gathered but the result (v18).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The miraculous equalization: those who gathered more had nothing left over; those who gathered less had no shortage. The result was always exactly one omer per person. Paul cites this verse verbatim in 2 Cor 8:15 (&ldquo;as it is written, he who gathered much had nothing left over, and he who gathered little had no lack&rdquo;) in his appeal for the Corinthians to share generously with the Jerusalem poor. The manna's miraculous equality is Paul's model for economic justice within the body of Christ.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;No one is to keep any of it until morning.&rdquo; The prohibition of overnight hoarding is the test's core: will Israel trust that tomorrow's provision will come? The command attacks the security-through-stockpiling instinct. The daily-bread economy requires daily faith. Jesus's &ldquo;give us this day our daily bread&rdquo; (Matt 6:11) echoes precisely this Exodus pattern: the <em>davar yom beyomo</em> (each day's portion, v4) is the model for the Lord's Prayer's petition.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Some kept it until morning; it bred worms and smelled. Moses was angry. The immediate consequence of hoarding — corruption and stench — confirms the rule. The hoarding instinct is not just disobedience but self-defeating: the surplus rots. The spiritual parallel: trust in self-provision instead of divine provision yields corruption, not security. The same imagery governs Jesus's warnings about storing earthly treasure (Matt 6:19-21).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Each morning everyone gathered as much as needed; when the sun grew hot, it melted. The daily rhythm of provision and limitation: the manna is available only in the early morning, before the heat. This time-restriction reinforces the daily-dependence structure — one cannot stock up by gathering extra before noon. The provision is generous but disciplined: enough, when needed, not whenever convenient.</p>",
    "22": "<p>On the sixth day they find a double portion. The community leaders report this to Moses — they notice the anomaly and bring it to YHWH's representative for interpretation. The community's observation and question model the proper response to YHWH's unexpected provision: report it to the interpreter rather than simply consuming it without understanding.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;Tomorrow is a Sabbath rest (<em>shabbaton</em>), a holy Sabbath (<em>shabbat kodesh</em>) to YHWH.&rdquo; The first formal identification of the Sabbath day in the Torah. The double term <em>shabbaton shabbat</em> (Sabbath rest, holy Sabbath) emphasizes both the rest and the holiness of the day. The Sabbath precedes Sinai — it is built into the manna's provision structure before it is commanded as law. The theological implication: the Sabbath rest is YHWH's gift, not first a human obligation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The manna kept until the Sabbath morning does not spoil. The supernatural preservation (contra v20 where overnight keeping produced worms) confirms that the Sabbath double-portion is a deliberate divine provision. The same God who caused spoilage to punish hoarding on ordinary days prevents spoilage to enable Sabbath rest. YHWH's actions are coherent with his stated purposes, not arbitrary.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;Eat it today, for today is a Sabbath to YHWH; today you will not find it on the ground.&rdquo; The threefold &ldquo;today&rdquo; (<em>hayom</em>) underlines the Sabbath's present-tense character: rest is for this day, not deferred. The Sabbath is not a future aspiration but a present institution. Hebrews 4:7-11 develops the Sabbath-rest typology through Ps 95: there remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God, accessible now through faith, not waiting for the land.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The six-day/seventh-day structure articulated as rule: &ldquo;Six days you are to gather it; but on the seventh day, the Sabbath, there will be none.&rdquo; The absence of manna on the Sabbath is not deprivation but the structure of the gift: the sixth day's double portion is sufficient. YHWH does not provide on the Sabbath because provision-for-Sabbath is already given on the sixth. The Sabbath economy is built on anticipatory generosity, not on-demand supply.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Some of the people go out on the seventh day to gather and find nothing. The violation is not penalized by YHWH here — the empty-handed return is itself the consequence. The pattern: YHWH warns, some disobey, the consequence is exactly what was promised (nothing to gather), and YHWH then speaks (v28). The graduated discipline — first the consequence itself, then the divine rebuke — shows patience in instruction before penalty.</p>",
    "28": "<p>YHWH's rebuke: &ldquo;How long will you refuse to keep my commands and my instructions?&rdquo; The rhetorical question — <em>ad matai me'antam</em> — is not information-seeking but confrontational. The Sabbath test reveals the fundamental issue: covenant obedience requires trusting YHWH's provision structure even when there is no visible reason to stop gathering. The Sabbath is the paradigmatic test of faith because it prohibits the most natural action (providing for oneself) in favor of trusting YHWH's prior provision.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;See — YHWH has given you the Sabbath; that is why on the sixth day he gives you two days' food.&rdquo; The Sabbath is named as YHWH's gift (<em>natan lachem hashabat</em>). The gift-logic of the Sabbath: YHWH gives the rest by providing double beforehand. The command to &ldquo;stay where you are — no one is to go out on the seventh day&rdquo; establishes the boundary within which Sabbath rest is experienced. The Sabbath rest is not merely the absence of labor but active remaining in YHWH's provision.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The terse summary: &ldquo;So the people rested on the seventh day.&rdquo; One verse for the first observed Sabbath — contrasting with the extensive instruction that preceded it. The brevity captures the Sabbath's essence: it is rest, not activity; the one day when the narrator has almost nothing to record because the action is ceasing from action.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The people name it manna — confirming the wordplay of v15. The physical description: white like coriander seed, tasted like honey wafers. Num 11:7-8 adds that it looked like bdellium (a translucent resin) and could be ground, cooked, and made into cakes tasting of cream or olive oil. The multiple descriptions suggest different preparations. The honey-taste points forward to the Promised Land's defining characteristic — a land flowing with milk and honey — present already in the wilderness provision.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The jar of manna as memorial — an omer to be kept &ldquo;for your future generations, so they can see the bread I fed you in the wilderness when I brought you out of Egypt.&rdquo; The preservation of the sign is an act of catechetical theology: future generations will see the actual manna and know YHWH fed their ancestors. Heb 9:4 lists the golden jar of manna as one of the three items kept inside the ark of the covenant (along with Aaron's budded rod and the stone tablets) — the ark as a repository of sign-objects for covenantal memory.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Aaron is told to take a jar (<em>tzintzenat</em>) and place an omer of manna in it. The placement &ldquo;before YHWH&rdquo; is proleptic — the ark does not yet exist. The narrator places the institution in its canonical context (before the Testimony = before the ark), acknowledging that the final arrangement belongs to the completed tabernacle. This literary technique (placing an institution in its permanent home even before that home exists) is common in the Pentateuch.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;As YHWH had commanded Moses, Aaron placed it before the Testimony.&rdquo; The Testimony (<em>ha'edut</em>) is the tablets of the covenant that would reside in the ark. The manna is preserved alongside the law as a witness to both YHWH's provision and Israel's obedience. The juxtaposition is significant: the law (what YHWH requires) and the manna (what YHWH provides) are kept together as the dual testimony of the covenant relationship.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The forty-year summary: Israel ate manna until they reached settled land — until they came to the border of Canaan. Josh 5:12 records the manna's cessation the day after they ate the produce of Canaan. The forty years is both a duration and a theological period: the wilderness generation passed away, a new generation was raised, and the provision sustained them all. The manna narrative thus frames the entire wilderness period between ch 16 (one month in) and Josh 5:12 (entering the land).</p>",
    "36": "<p>Parenthetical note: the omer is one-tenth of an ephah. A scribal gloss for readers unfamiliar with the measure, suggesting the chapter was edited for later audiences to whom the omer was an archaic unit. The ephah (a standard dry measure, approximately 22 liters) provides the reference point. Such parenthetical metrology is common in later biblical texts that preserve archaic terms.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>The Israelites move from the wilderness of Sin to Rephidim — location debated, but probably in the southern Sinai Peninsula, near Horeb. The phrase &ldquo;as YHWH directed&rdquo; (<em>al pi YHWH</em>) reflects the cloud-guidance of 13:21-22 and Num 9:15-23. At Rephidim there is no water — the provision of manna (ch 16) is followed immediately by the water crisis. The Wilderness testing alternates between provision and crisis, building a cumulative pattern of YHWH's care through successive emergencies.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The people &ldquo;quarreled&rdquo; (<em>vayarev</em>) with Moses — the verb gives the place its name Meribah (v7). Moses's counter-question: &ldquo;Why do you quarrel with me? Why do you test YHWH?&rdquo; The two verbs — <em>rav</em> (quarrel/strive) and <em>nasa</em> (test/prove) — define the theological crisis: the people are testing YHWH's reliability, putting him on trial. Ps 95:8 and Heb 3:7-11 use Meribah as the paradigm of the hardened heart that refuses trust.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The complaint escalates: &ldquo;Why did you bring us out of Egypt to kill us and our children and our livestock with thirst?&rdquo; The same Egypt-idealization as ch 16, now weaponized as an accusation of murderous intent. The thirst-death narrative is the wilderness community's worst crisis so far. The word &ldquo;thirst&rdquo; (<em>tzama</em>) will become a Psalm imagery for spiritual longing — Ps 42:1-2 (&ldquo;as a deer pants for streams of water, so my soul pants for you, O God&rdquo;) and Ps 63:1 (&ldquo;my soul thirsts for you, my flesh faints for you, as in a dry and weary land&rdquo;) spiritualize the Rephidim thirst.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Moses's cry to YHWH: &ldquo;What shall I do with this people? They are almost ready to stone me!&rdquo; The prayer is panic and faith together — panic at the imminent violence, faith that YHWH has an answer. Moses does not attempt to solve the water problem himself or to pacify the crowd; he goes immediately to YHWH. This prophetic reflex — problem → prayer, not problem → strategy — is the model of prophetic leadership throughout Israel's history (Jer 12:1-4; 15:15-18; Hab 1:2-3).</p>",
    "5": "<p>YHWH's response: take the staff, take some elders, go in front of the people. The staff — which struck the Nile (7:20) and parted the sea (14:16) — is the instrument of the rock-water miracle. The elders witness the event, providing communal authentication. The structure mirrors the Exodus events: staff + YHWH's word + water. YHWH reuses the same instrument in a new element, showing the consistency of his method.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;I will stand before you there on the rock at Horeb; strike the rock, and water will come out of it.&rdquo; YHWH positions himself at the rock — the divine presence is at the point of impact before Moses strikes. The struck rock becomes a Christological type: Paul in 1 Cor 10:4 identifies it explicitly — &ldquo;the rock was Christ.&rdquo; The water that flows from the struck rock, sustaining life in the desert, is the type of the Spirit flowing from the crucified Christ (John 7:37-39; 19:34). The parallel is structural: Christ is struck (crucified); living water flows for the life of those who follow.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The double name — Massah (Testing) and Meribah (Quarreling) — memorializes both Israel's failure and YHWH's provision in the same place-name. Ps 95:8-9 quotes this episode as the paradigm of the hard heart: &ldquo;do not harden your hearts, as at Meribah, as on the day of Massah in the wilderness, where your fathers tested me.&rdquo; Heb 3:7-11 and 3:15 cite Ps 95 as a warning to the church: the Meribah generation is the negative example for all who hear YHWH's voice and must choose whether to trust.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Amalekites attack at Rephidim without warning or provocation recorded in the text. Deut 25:17-18 adds the detail: they attacked from the rear, targeting the weak and stragglers, &ldquo;showing no fear of God.&rdquo; The Amalekites are the descendants of Amalek son of Eliphaz son of Esau (Gen 36:12) — the Esau-Israel conflict carried forward into the next generation. The attack during Israel's wilderness march becomes the paradigmatic act of predatory opposition to YHWH's people.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Joshua's narrative debut — his full name <em>Yehoshua</em> (YHWH saves) is given here without introduction, suggesting his role was already known to the original audience. He is Moses's military commander from this point forward. Moses, Aaron, and Hur occupy the hilltop while Joshua fights below — the vertical structure of the battle (prayer from above, sword from below) establishes the principle that Israel's military victories are won by YHWH through the intercession of the appointed leader, not by military strength alone.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Joshua fights; Moses, Aaron, and Hur climb the hill. The separation of the spiritual and military dimensions of the battle — intercession above, fighting below — is a structural feature of Israel's holy war theology. The intercessor on the hill is as essential as the soldier in the valley. This pattern recurs: Samuel's intercession at Mizpah (1 Sam 7:5-12), Elijah on Carmel (1 Kgs 18:36-39), the battle won while the king is still praying (2 Chr 20:20-22).</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;When Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed; when he lowered his hand, Amalek prevailed.&rdquo; The raised hands (<em>yad ramah</em>) — the posture of prayer, dependence, and surrender — are the instrument of YHWH's power in the battle. The lowered hands are not sin but human limitation; the problem is exhaustion, not unfaith. The structure illustrates that YHWH's power flows through sustained dependence, not occasional petition. Sustained intercession, not momentary prayer, wins.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The communal support of the intercessor — Aaron and Hur on each side, holding Moses's hands up until sunset. Moses cannot sustain the posture alone; his colleagues uphold him. The image became formative for Christian theology of communal intercession: the leader's prayers require the support of the community. Aaron is the priest; Hur (2:14 is sometimes read as the same figure; 1 Chr 2:19-20 identifies him as a Judahite) provides lay support. Priestly and lay support together sustain the prophetic intercession through exhaustion to victory.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Joshua overwhelmed (<em>vayachalosh</em>) the Amalekites — the verb is rare, meaning to weaken, disable, make powerless. The totality of the victory is signaled by the unusual term. The victory is ascribed to the sword while being caused by the raised hands — both are necessary, neither sufficient without the other. Human effort and divine power are both fully present in the battle's resolution.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;Write this on a scroll as a reminder and recite it in Joshua's ears.&rdquo; The first command to write in the Torah. The written memorial (<em>zikaron</em>) serves both preservation and transmission: the scroll endures; Joshua hears and carries the tradition into the next generation. YHWH's declaration that &ldquo;I will completely blot out the memory of Amalek from under heaven&rdquo; is the theological stake of the war — it is not merely a military conflict but a theological annihilation. Deut 25:19 commands Israel to &ldquo;blot out the memory of Amalek.&rdquo;</p>",
    "15": "<p>Moses builds an altar named YHWH-Nissi (YHWH is my banner/standard). The altar names YHWH as the military standard under which Israel fought. In ANE armies, the standard-bearer was the focus of rallying — the banner around which troops gathered. Naming YHWH as the banner declares that Israel's military cohesion and confidence is centered on YHWH himself, not on human commanders or their symbols.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;A hand upon the throne of YHWH! YHWH will be at war with Amalek from generation to generation.&rdquo; The oath formula over YHWH's throne declares the war with Amalek as cosmic and permanent — not a single battle but an ongoing conflict in YHWH's history. The OT carries this through: Saul's failure to execute this command against Agag the Amalekite king costs him the kingdom (1 Sam 15); Haman the Agagite (Amalekite descendant) threatens to destroy Israel in the book of Esther. The &ldquo;generation to generation&rdquo; war is the OT's way of naming the persistent opposition of anti-covenant powers to YHWH's purposes.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>Jethro, priest of Midian, hears of all that YHWH did for Moses and for Israel. The outside witness — a non-Israelite religious leader — hears the Exodus news and comes. The pattern of Gentile recognition of YHWH's power runs through the OT: Rahab (Josh 2:9-11), the Queen of Sheba (1 Kgs 10:6-9), Naaman (2 Kgs 5:15), the sailors with Jonah (Jon 1:16). The nations' response to YHWH's acts is the expected outcome of the Exodus: &ldquo;that all the peoples of the earth might know that the hand of YHWH is mighty&rdquo; (Josh 4:24).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Zipporah had been &ldquo;sent back&rdquo; (<em>shillucheyha</em>) by Moses — presumably during or before the confrontation with Pharaoh, when the dangerous mission made her presence unwise. The exact timing is unclear; the verse references an earlier separation. Her return with Jethro completes a family reunion at the mountain of God. The two sons and wife arriving at the sacred mountain anticipate the later gathering of all Israel there.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Gershom's name — &ldquo;I have been a foreigner in a foreign land&rdquo; (<em>ger hayiti bearetz nokhriya</em>). The name-etymology encapsulates Moses's Midianite sojourn but also Israel's condition in Egypt. The <em>ger</em> (sojourner, alien) is a significant legal category in the Torah: Israel is to treat the stranger with justice because they were strangers in Egypt (Exod 22:21; Lev 19:34; Deut 10:19). Moses's own name for his son preserves the memory of his father's alien experience.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Eliezer's name — &ldquo;my father's God was my help; he rescued me from Pharaoh's sword.&rdquo; The name is a retrospective testimony: YHWH's protection of Moses from Pharaoh (Exod 2:15) is memorialized in the name of a son. The two sons together encapsulate Moses's wilderness experience: Gershom = the alien life; Eliezer = the divine rescue. Family names as theological testimony is a consistent OT practice.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jethro arrives at &ldquo;the mountain of God&rdquo; — Horeb/Sinai. The Midianite priest arrives at YHWH's sacred mountain before Israel's covenant is given there. The geographical setting is significant: the mountain is YHWH's territory, yet Jethro has access. This Gentile accessibility to the mountain of YHWH anticipates the eschatological vision of Isa 2:2-3: &ldquo;All the nations will stream to the mountain of YHWH.&rdquo; The foreigner arrives at the holy mountain with an offering and leaves having given wisdom to Israel's leader.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The announcement of arrival — Jethro sends word ahead. The courtesy protocol of ANE hospitality: messengers precede guests. Moses's response (v7) matches the formal greeting expected: going out, bowing, kissing. The relational texture of this chapter humanizes the narrative between the dramatic wilderness crises and the consuming fire of Sinai.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Moses goes out to meet his father-in-law, bows down (<em>vayishtachu lo</em>), and kisses him. The bow is the honor-greeting for an elder or superior — the same word used for worshipping YHWH, though here in a social rather than religious register. Moses does not treat Jethro's foreign status as disqualifying: he gives him full filial respect. They greet, ask about each other's welfare (<em>vayishal ish lere'ehu leshalom</em>), then go into the tent.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Moses recounts to Jethro &ldquo;all that YHWH had done to Pharaoh and Egypt for Israel's sake, and all the hardship they had encountered, and how YHWH had delivered them.&rdquo; The recounting is the missionary act — proclaiming YHWH's saving deeds to a Gentile. This is the narrative structure of evangelism in the OT: the telling of YHWH's acts produces recognition (v9-11), worship (v12), and wisdom (v17-23). Jethro's response models the ideal Gentile response to the Exodus story.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jethro &ldquo;rejoiced&rdquo; (<em>vayichad</em>) over all the good YHWH had done. The verb <em>chada</em> means to be joyful, glad, exultant — a strong positive response. This Gentile joy at Israel's deliverance is the first instance of the nations' blessing of YHWH in the wilderness narrative. The eschatological promise (that the nations will rejoice in YHWH's salvation of Israel, Isa 66:10; Ps 67; Rom 15:10) has its prototype here.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jethro's blessing-confession: &ldquo;Blessed be YHWH who delivered you from the Egyptians and from Pharaoh, and who delivered the people from under the Egyptians' hand.&rdquo; The covenant blessing-formula (<em>baruch YHWH</em>) is applied by a Midianite to Israel's God. Jethro's prayer is the first extended Gentile blessing of YHWH in the Torah. His threefold &ldquo;delivered&rdquo; mirrors the three-fold deliverance from Egypt, from Pharaoh, and from Egypt's power — a comprehensive redemption.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Now I know that YHWH is greater than all other gods.&rdquo; <em>Yada'ti ki gadol YHWH mikol ha'elohim</em> — using the same knowledge-verb that Pharaoh refused: &ldquo;I do not know YHWH&rdquo; (5:2). Jethro's confession is the theological counterpoint to Pharaoh's denial. The same evidence (the Exodus events) produces opposite responses: Pharaoh's heart hardens; Jethro acknowledges YHWH's supremacy. The addition &ldquo;for in the thing where they dealt arrogantly, he was above them&rdquo; shows that Jethro understands the Exodus as YHWH's response to Egyptian pride — the very point of the plagues.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jethro brings a burnt offering (<em>olah</em>) and sacrifices to God. Aaron and all the elders of Israel eat bread with Moses's father-in-law before God. The shared covenantal meal — eating together before YHWH — constitutes the community that transcends ethnic boundary. The Midianite priest presides at the offering; Israel's priest (Aaron) and leaders (elders) eat together with him. This is a model of Gentile inclusion in the worship of YHWH before the Sinai covenant creates the formal boundary. The meal before God (cf. Exod 24:9-11) is the highest form of communal fellowship in the OT.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The judicial burden — Moses serves as judge from morning to evening. The community's need for dispute resolution and Torah-instruction is a new institutional problem. The formerly-enslaved community has been freed from Pharaoh's administrative system and lacks its own. Moses is the sole intermediary. Deut 1:9-18 presents Moses's own recollection of this event, emphasizing that the burden was too great for one person: &ldquo;I cannot bear you alone; YHWH your God has multiplied you.&rdquo;</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jethro's observational question: &ldquo;Why do you alone sit as judge, with all the people standing around you from morning to evening?&rdquo; The question is not rhetorical but diagnostic — Jethro has watched and assessed the system. His assessment follows in v17-18. The outsider's perspective is what enables the critique: someone too close to the system cannot see its structural problems. The willingness to receive this critique from a Midianite is a remarkable mark of Moses's humility.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Moses's explanation: &ldquo;The people come to me to seek God's will (<em>lidrosh Elohim</em>).&rdquo; The judicial role is simultaneously prophetic: Moses hears cases and mediates divine instruction. The phrase <em>darash Elohim</em> (seek God) is the technical term for consulting YHWH through his representative — the same phrase used for consulting prophets and priests throughout the historical books (1 Kgs 22:5; 2 Kgs 22:13; Isa 8:19). Moses's role is not merely legal but revelatory.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Whenever they have a dispute, it is brought to me; I decide between the parties and inform them of God's decrees and instructions (<em>chuqqot ha'elohim vetorotav</em>).&rdquo; Moses's dual function: judicial adjudication between parties + instruction in divine Torah. The phrase <em>chuqqot vetorot</em> (statutes and instructions) anticipates the Sinai law's vocabulary. Moses is delivering Torah before Sinai — the general moral and covenantal principles YHWH has communicated — as the basis for case decisions.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;What you are doing is not good.&rdquo; Jethro's direct assessment uses the same language as YHWH's assessment of uncreated elements in Gen 1: &ldquo;it is not good&rdquo; (Gen 2:18). The bluntness is striking from a father-in-law to the deliverer of Israel. Moses has not set up a bad system through negligence but has simply not recognized the structural limits of single-point leadership. Jethro's critique is administrative wisdom, not moral accusation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;You will surely wear yourself out (<em>nivol tibol</em>) — and these people too.&rdquo; The Hebrew infinitive absolute for emphasis: you will absolutely exhaust yourself. The dual harm — to Moses and to the people — shows that bad institutional structure damages everyone, not just the overwhelmed leader. Leadership burnout is not a modern pathology but an ancient one Jethro names directly. The remedy is not Moses working harder but structural reform.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jethro's counsel: Moses retains the representative role — &ldquo;be the people's representative before God, bring cases to God.&rdquo; The high-altitude, high-stakes matters (cases requiring direct divine consultation) remain Moses's responsibility. The delegation reduces volume, not importance. Moses remains the link between YHWH and Israel; what he delegates is the routine administration that does not require that direct mediation.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Teach them his decrees and instructions; show them the way to live and the duties they are to perform.&rdquo; The preventive measure: comprehensive Torah-instruction prevents disputes by forming a community that knows YHWH's will. The judicial system's long-term health depends not on better adjudication but on better formation. The priest-teacher role (Lev 10:11; Deut 33:10; Mal 2:7) carries this function forward: teaching Torah is the primary priestly contribution to communal health.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The criteria for appointed judges: capable (<em>anshei chayil</em>), God-fearing (<em>yir'ei Elohim</em>), trustworthy (<em>anshei emet</em>), anti-corrupt (<em>soné vetza</em>). The four criteria are the first articulation of judicial standards in the Torah. The second criterion — &ldquo;fearing God&rdquo; — grounds judicial integrity in theology: the judge who fears YHWH will judge without favoritism because he fears the higher Judge. This principle governs judicial ethics throughout the OT (Lev 19:15; Deut 1:17; 16:19) and appears in Jesus's parable of the unjust judge (Luke 18:1-8) by contrast.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The tiered judiciary: bring major cases to Moses, decide minor cases themselves. The hierarchy — officers of thousands, hundreds, fifties, tens — mirrors ANE administrative military-civilian structures. Deut 16:18-20 and 17:8-13 develop the formal judicial system with local judges and a supreme court (the priests and the judge in the central sanctuary) for difficult cases. Jethro's proposal is the proto-text of Israel's judicial constitution.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;If you do this, and God so commands (<em>vetzivecha Elohim</em>), you will be able to stand the strain.&rdquo; The crucial qualifier: Jethro's advice is contingent on divine authorization. He does not claim independent authority over Israel's institutional structure; he presents a plan and defers to YHWH's confirmation. Moses subsequently implements the plan (v24-26) — implying the divine authorization was given, though the narrative does not record a formal consultation. Deut 1:14-15 implies Moses also consulted the people.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;Moses listened to his father-in-law and did everything he said.&rdquo; The great lawgiver and prophet accepts administrative counsel from his Midianite father-in-law. Moses's teachability — the absence of defensiveness in a position of unchallenged authority — is presented as a virtue. The OT wisdom tradition consistently values the counsel of the wise regardless of origin: wisdom is recognized and received, not guarded as an ethnic privilege.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Moses chooses capable men from all Israel and appoints them over thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens. The scale of the hierarchy — four levels of authority — reflects a large community. The selection criterion remains &ldquo;capable men&rdquo; (<em>anshei chayil</em>), though the full four-fold standard of v21 is compressed. The appointment is from &ldquo;all Israel&rdquo; — not just Levites or a priestly class but the capable from every tribe.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The implementation works as designed: routine cases handled locally; difficult cases brought to Moses. The simple word &ldquo;simple&rdquo; (<em>qatan</em>, small/minor) and &ldquo;difficult&rdquo; (<em>qasheh</em>, hard) establish the judgment category. The Sinai covenant will later provide the substantive content — the Torah — that judges will apply to cases. Jethro's administrative reform creates the structure into which the Sinai law will be poured.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Jethro returns to his own country before the Sinai theophany. The timing is structurally significant: the Gentile witness exits before the exclusively-Israelite covenant is ratified at Sinai. Jethro belongs to the prologue to Sinai — the witness who authenticates YHWH's acts from outside the covenant community — but not to the covenant itself. The Kenite/Midianite tradition preserves ongoing connection: Jethro's descendants are associated with Israel in Judg 1:16 and 4:11. His departure is not rejection but the return of a co-laborer to his own sphere.</p>"
  },
  "1": {
    "11": "<p>The historical context of the Exodus is debated: the most common evangelical dating places the Exodus ca. 1446 BCE (the 'early date,' based on 1 Kings 6:1's 480 years from Exodus to Solomon's temple ca. 966 BCE), during Thutmose III's reign. The 'late date' (ca. 1270-1250 BCE, during Ramesses II's reign) is favored by many archaeologists based on the cities Pithom and Ramesses mentioned in Exod 1:11. The Merneptah Stele (ca. 1208 BCE) mentions Israel as a people already in Canaan, providing a terminus ad quem. The question remains open; the theological significance of the Exodus is independent of the exact date.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The Passover (Heb. <em>pesach</em>) became the foundational festival of Israelite identity — the annual re-enactment and remembrance of YHWH's redemptive act. The Passover Seder developed in the Second Temple period and was the meal Jesus shared with his disciples on the night of his arrest. Jesus's identification of the cup with his blood and the bread with his body (Luke 22:19-20) reinterprets the Passover meal through the lens of his approaching death: the new exodus is accomplished through his death as the new Passover lamb. Paul's 'Christ our Passover has been sacrificed' (1 Cor 5:7) is the theological crystallization of this identification.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>The Sinai covenant is the central structuring event of the OT: it establishes the constitutional framework of Israel's relationship with YHWH. Its suzerainty-treaty structure (parallel to Hittite treaties: preamble, historical prologue, stipulations, blessings/curses, witnesses) places YHWH as the great king and Israel as his vassal. The Decalogue (20:1-17) is the covenant's summary stipulations. The Book of the Covenant (20:22-23:33) elaborates case law. The covenant-inauguration ceremony (24:1-11) seals the relationship with blood and a covenant meal. Hebrews 12:18-24 contrasts the terrors of Sinai with the joy of Zion — the old covenant's thunders and fire point forward to the new covenant's completed mediation in Christ.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>The tabernacle instructions (Exod 25-31) and their execution (35-40) occupy more chapters in Exodus than any other section. The tabernacle is the theological center of the wilderness narrative: YHWH's presence (kavod) dwelling among Israel in the portable sanctuary. Its structure (outer court, holy place, most holy place) reflects the graduated holiness of sacred space that culminates in the ark and mercy seat where YHWH meets with Israel. Solomon's temple is the permanent version of this portable structure. The NT develops the typological chain: tabernacle → temple → Christ's body (John 2:21) → the church as temple (1 Cor 3:16) → the new Jerusalem as the final dwelling of God with his people (Rev 21:3).</p>"
  }
}

CHRIST = {
  "12": {
    "13": "<p>A fulfillment: 'When I see the blood, I will pass over you, and no plague will befall you to destroy you when I strike the land of Egypt.' The Passover blood on the doorposts is the OT's most developed type of substitutionary atonement: an innocent lamb dies; its blood marks the household; the destroyer passes over those marked. Paul makes the typological identification explicit: 'Christ our Passover has been sacrificed' (1 Cor 5:7). John structures his Gospel so the crucifixion occurs when the Passover lambs are being slaughtered in the temple (John 19:14), and notes the non-breaking of bones fulfills Exod 12:46. The Passover is not merely a historical parallel but the interpretive key YHWH planted in Israel's annual liturgy to explain, centuries in advance, the theological meaning of the cross.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "22": "<p>A type: 'And the people of Israel went into the midst of the sea on dry ground, the waters being a wall to them on their right hand and on their left.' Paul explicitly calls the Red Sea crossing a baptismal type: 'all were baptized into Moses in the cloud and in the sea' (1 Cor 10:1-2). The structure is identical to Christian baptism: God's redemptive act through a threshold of water, from slavery into freedom, into covenant relationship. But the antitype is greater: baptism into Christ is death and resurrection with Christ (Rom 6:3-4), not merely deliverance from one earthly power. Moses led Israel through the sea; Christ leads his people through death itself.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "15": "<p>A type: 'It is manna' (or 'What is it?') — bread from heaven that YHWH provides. Jesus in John 6 identifies himself as the fulfillment of the manna type: 'Your fathers ate the manna in the wilderness, and they died. This is the bread that comes down from heaven, so that one may eat of it and not die. I am the living bread that came down from heaven' (John 6:49-51). The typological contrast is sharp: the manna sustained physical life temporarily; Christ gives eternal life. The manna was perishable; Christ is permanent. The manna was provided daily; Christ is given once. The Lord's Supper as ongoing eating of Christ (John 6:53-56) is the enacted fulfillment of the manna's promise.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "22": "<p>A type: 'There I will meet with you, and from above the mercy seat, from between the two cherubim that are on the ark of the testimony, I will speak with you.' The mercy seat (<em>kapporet</em>, from <em>kipper</em>, to atone/cover) is the lid of the ark, sprinkled with blood on Yom Kippur. Paul in Romans 3:25 calls Christ a <em>hilasterion</em> — the LXX word for the mercy seat. Christ is both the priest who offers the sacrifice and the mercy seat on which the blood is placed; he is both offerer and the place of offering, the one who makes atonement and the locus where God and humanity meet. The tabernacle's most restricted and holy object — accessible only once a year, only by the high priest, only with blood — is fulfilled in Christ who provides permanent access to God.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('exodus')
    merge_echo(e, ECHO)
    save_echo('exodus', e)

    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'exodus', c)

    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', c)

    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'exodus', c)

    print('exodus: all 4 layers written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
